146
00:07:52,400 --> 00:07:53,762
The first principle of the art

147
00:07:53,762 --> 00:07:55,303
is not to rely on tricks of technique.

148
00:07:55,303 --> 00:07:57,845
Most swordsmen make too much of technique,

149
00:07:57,845 --> 00:07:59,927
sometimes making it their chief concern.

150
00:08:00,338 --> 00:08:05,740
What we've seen is when you have the ability to use a lot of fancy graphics effects,

151
00:08:05,740 --> 00:08:11,442
it allows you to sort of get more lax about some of the core art principles, art values.

152
00:08:11,442 --> 00:08:17,643
Because we can't rely on those effects, we almost are exclusively on core art principles and values.

153
00:08:17,643 --> 00:08:24,885
And so this provides us a razor focus, and we actually believe that because they're so core to art.

154
00:08:25,263 --> 00:08:28,625
that any game title or anyone that's making something,

155
00:08:28,625 --> 00:08:30,746
if they pay attention to these core principles,

156
00:08:30,746 --> 00:08:32,668
it just makes their work better.

157
00:08:32,668 --> 00:08:34,009
And oftentimes we forget that.

158
00:08:34,009 --> 00:08:35,850
We see that with students.

159
00:08:35,850 --> 00:08:37,951
We see that with professionals,

160
00:08:37,951 --> 00:08:40,033
that the computer gets the better of them,

161
00:08:40,033 --> 00:08:43,275
and they rely too much on sort of the whiz bang stuff

162
00:08:43,275 --> 00:08:46,016
and not enough on those core fundamentals.

163
00:08:46,016 --> 00:08:48,758
So when I talk about the core fundamentals,

164
00:08:48,758 --> 00:08:51,500
which is mostly what I'll be talking about today,

165
00:08:51,500 --> 00:08:52,201
this is what I mean.

166
00:08:52,201 --> 00:08:54,622
Talking about composition, value.

167
00:08:55,627 --> 00:09:02,471
palette, texture, shape, storytelling, cadence,

168
00:09:02,471 --> 00:09:03,712
and performance.

169
00:09:03,712 --> 00:09:05,553
And these are the topics that I'll be going over

170
00:09:05,553 --> 00:09:06,434
in further detail today.

171
00:09:06,434 --> 00:09:08,975
And something that you'll notice is what I tend to do

172
00:09:08,975 --> 00:09:11,196
is move from large to small.

173
00:09:11,196 --> 00:09:12,817
This is how you should build up anything,

174
00:09:12,817 --> 00:09:15,579
like a painting or any art piece, really.

175
00:09:16,005 --> 00:09:30,167
A lot of people will tend to get focused on texture too quickly without having settled these other core principles. And so as I go through this talk I'll kind of be moving through it from that big with big to small in mind.

176
00:09:30,167 --> 00:09:34,888
So, starting we'll talk about focusing on what matters.

177
00:09:34,888 --> 00:09:43,270
We spent a lot of time thinking about composition and I flow, just because we generally again you're on rails we generally know where, where you're looking at what you're looking at.

178
00:09:43,563 --> 00:09:48,404
However, early on in our titles, we weren't very good at this because a lot of us were

179
00:09:48,404 --> 00:09:52,705
used to working on first-person shooters or other titles, and we focused the majority

180
00:09:52,705 --> 00:09:55,466
of our attention around this area.

181
00:09:55,466 --> 00:10:00,387
So we put a lot of detail into our trackside objects, into our buildings, and what we found

182
00:10:00,387 --> 00:10:04,249
was it just didn't have a lot of bang for the buck.

183
00:10:04,249 --> 00:10:06,169
That just doesn't take much of the real estate.

184
00:10:07,478 --> 00:10:09,900
What we call it is the wedge, but this takes about 80%

185
00:10:09,900 --> 00:10:11,902
of the real estate of the screen.

186
00:10:11,902 --> 00:10:14,063
So it's critical that the read of this

187
00:10:14,063 --> 00:10:17,586
is the most important part of the whole scene.

188
00:10:17,586 --> 00:10:21,189
The sky, the road, getting that right, that's everything.

189
00:10:21,189 --> 00:10:23,471
And you can let a lot of this stuff go

190
00:10:23,471 --> 00:10:25,253
because we know that this is taking up

191
00:10:25,253 --> 00:10:26,714
so much real estate in our scene

192
00:10:26,714 --> 00:10:28,295
and is really what the player is looking at.

193
00:10:30,026 --> 00:10:31,727
We spent so much time thinking about this

194
00:10:31,727 --> 00:10:33,807
that what we did was we developed a system

195
00:10:33,807 --> 00:10:36,048
where if you're familiar with the rule of thirds

196
00:10:36,048 --> 00:10:38,189
where compositionally you split your frame

197
00:10:38,189 --> 00:10:41,811
into three parts, we did that here.

198
00:10:41,811 --> 00:10:44,392
And then we mapped out where the intersection points

199
00:10:44,392 --> 00:10:46,893
of those thirds were.

200
00:10:46,893 --> 00:10:48,753
And then we took it a step further.

201
00:10:48,753 --> 00:10:53,035
And what we found was that the focus of the viewer,

202
00:10:53,035 --> 00:10:54,796
the focus of the player tended to be

203
00:10:54,796 --> 00:10:56,917
in this sort of red diamond in the center.

204
00:10:57,461 --> 00:11:08,725
And we even backed this up with, we had Kinect eye tracking at the time, and we looked at a whole group of players to see where were they generally looking, and it tended to fall right in this area.

205
00:11:08,725 --> 00:11:15,167
So we know that when you're driving, this is the majority of where your focus is. So this caused us to prioritize our scene accordingly.

206
00:11:15,167 --> 00:11:22,869
Our P1, all the assets where we would spend the most amount of time, the most amount of polish, bug fix, would all happen within this area.

207
00:11:23,952 --> 00:11:25,313
This would be our P2 area.

208
00:11:25,313 --> 00:11:27,916
This would be the area that we would fix things,

209
00:11:27,916 --> 00:11:29,657
but it would be less critical.

210
00:11:29,657 --> 00:11:31,459
And what we found with the P3 area

211
00:11:31,459 --> 00:11:33,801
was you could almost ignore it.

212
00:11:33,801 --> 00:11:36,923
I was amazed at the bugs that we would have in this area

213
00:11:36,923 --> 00:11:38,205
that seemed glaring to me

214
00:11:38,205 --> 00:11:40,026
because I was used to staring at the screen

215
00:11:40,026 --> 00:11:41,808
that people wouldn't see at all.

216
00:11:41,808 --> 00:11:45,151
Whole objects dropping out, the world missing.

217
00:11:45,151 --> 00:11:47,292
It's just, when you're focused on an area,

218
00:11:47,292 --> 00:11:49,534
it's very difficult to look anywhere else

219
00:11:49,534 --> 00:11:51,176
and people were just not looking out there.

220
00:11:51,623 --> 00:11:54,184
So it really just shows you how much composition matters

221
00:11:54,184 --> 00:11:59,207
and really not spreading your efforts out like peanut butter.

222
00:11:59,207 --> 00:12:00,948
So we use this tool so much that we actually

223
00:12:00,948 --> 00:12:03,129
created an in-game overlay that allowed you

224
00:12:03,129 --> 00:12:04,890
to see where you were looking.

225
00:12:04,890 --> 00:12:07,411
And we would have this on screen at all times

226
00:12:07,411 --> 00:12:09,673
so that as we're driving around, we can really

227
00:12:09,673 --> 00:12:12,654
see where is the focus, where is the player looking,

228
00:12:12,654 --> 00:12:16,056
and where do we need to focus on polishing our assets.

229
00:12:18,340 --> 00:12:24,882
The other thing that we noticed is that this focus did tend to shift depending on the context of the gameplay.

230
00:12:24,882 --> 00:12:28,882
So if you look at this area here, this is a user that's taking a difficult turn in the wet.

231
00:12:28,882 --> 00:12:34,784
And so as they're turning, their focus changes from being out in front of them to right at this corner.

232
00:12:34,784 --> 00:12:38,544
You naturally start to look down at the corner that you're taking.

233
00:12:38,544 --> 00:12:42,625
Your focus and your attention goes to that because you're in a high intense gameplay moment.

234
00:12:42,625 --> 00:12:46,026
This here is where you're straightening out.

235
00:12:46,252 --> 00:12:48,172
And what we found is then your focus shifts,

236
00:12:48,172 --> 00:12:50,053
it goes from being at the corner

237
00:12:50,053 --> 00:12:52,194
to up and out towards the horizon.

238
00:12:52,194 --> 00:12:53,655
So I'll talk about this later,

239
00:12:53,655 --> 00:12:56,376
but knowing that we tended to put our big moments

240
00:12:56,376 --> 00:12:58,237
or our big areas of visual interest,

241
00:12:58,237 --> 00:13:00,758
in this case, having a really compelling sky

242
00:13:00,758 --> 00:13:01,758
out in front of you,

243
00:13:01,758 --> 00:13:04,019
because we know that's what you're looking at at that time.

244
00:13:04,019 --> 00:13:08,821
So talking about the corner.

245
00:13:09,083 --> 00:13:12,926
What we did is if we know that you're looking at the corner at a particular time,

246
00:13:12,926 --> 00:13:17,028
that's where we'd spend a lot of our attention and focus and detail down on that corner.

