00:14:31,352 --> 00:14:32,914
and the amount we can spend on each asset.

268
00:14:32,914 --> 00:14:37,920
So next I want to talk about the frame

269
00:14:37,920 --> 00:14:39,622
and how we design for the frame.

270
00:14:40,943 --> 00:14:45,866
Because we're moving so quickly, the frame is really your impression of the scene.

271
00:14:45,866 --> 00:14:48,087
This is the part that we have to get photorealistic.

272
00:14:48,087 --> 00:14:52,929
And one of the biggest tools that we have to getting photorealistic visuals is around value.

273
00:14:52,929 --> 00:14:56,471
This is also true if you looked at paintings as well.

274
00:14:56,471 --> 00:15:07,537
So much so to the point that we would actually do blurred grayscale thumbnails of our scene just to make sure that our values were reading OK and that nothing was standing out.

275
00:15:08,354 --> 00:15:12,818
To actually call out this scene in particular, we used to really struggle with this, where

276
00:15:12,818 --> 00:15:17,702
we would have areas like our guardrail, if I show you over here, or areas like our road

277
00:15:17,702 --> 00:15:21,585
lines being too white or not cohesive.

278
00:15:21,585 --> 00:15:23,726
And what that does is contrast draws your eye.

279
00:15:23,726 --> 00:15:28,470
And what we found is that people are actually looking at the road lines and looking at the

280
00:15:28,470 --> 00:15:30,251
guardrails rather than looking at the car.

281
00:15:30,754 --> 00:15:34,475
And this created a non-cohesive scene,

282
00:15:34,475 --> 00:15:37,916
and it created sort of a discordance with the viewer.

283
00:15:37,916 --> 00:15:39,136
And so we really wanna make sure

284
00:15:39,136 --> 00:15:41,276
that we're balancing our values,

285
00:15:41,276 --> 00:15:43,317
make sure that they land in a photorealistic frame.

286
00:15:43,317 --> 00:15:46,638
How we do that, if anyone isn't familiar with this,

287
00:15:46,638 --> 00:15:50,899
is with the concept of authoring our textures color correct.

288
00:15:50,899 --> 00:15:52,619
So what we use, we have this thing called

289
00:15:52,619 --> 00:15:53,499
a color checker here.

290
00:15:53,499 --> 00:15:55,620
These are industry standard values.

291
00:15:56,037 --> 00:16:01,339
And what we'll do is we'll take a picture of something for a texture reference, and then we'll bring it into Photoshop.

292
00:16:01,339 --> 00:16:05,601
What happens when you take a picture of something in the real world is that it's colored by light.

293
00:16:05,601 --> 00:16:11,003
You can see that these are two very different scenes. One is in the overcast, one is on a bright sunny day.

294
00:16:11,003 --> 00:16:19,967
And what we're trying to do is we're trying to remove all of that light information, all of that color information, and get down to what is the base value for that color.

295
00:16:20,402 --> 00:16:22,862
And so we'll bring our textures into Photoshop

296
00:16:22,862 --> 00:16:25,142
and balance them because Photoshop knows

297
00:16:25,142 --> 00:16:28,523
what color this color checker needs to be,

298
00:16:28,523 --> 00:16:30,824
and they'll balance it to get the appropriate values.

299
00:16:30,824 --> 00:16:33,964
And this is key for us to get good values

300
00:16:33,964 --> 00:16:35,244
and good base values at the beginning

301
00:16:35,244 --> 00:16:36,605
when we're authoring our textures.

302
00:16:36,605 --> 00:16:40,225
So we even created the spectrum that shows

303
00:16:40,225 --> 00:16:44,066
these are where all the things in life,

304
00:16:44,066 --> 00:16:46,567
this isn't all of them, but it's a handful of common ones

305
00:16:46,567 --> 00:16:49,667
that we use in our game, fall on the value spectrum.

306
00:16:50,142 --> 00:16:51,822
And what this shows us is a couple of things.

307
00:16:51,822 --> 00:16:55,423
One is there tends to be what we call the art direction range.

308
00:16:55,423 --> 00:16:59,364
Almost nothing in real life goes above,

309
00:16:59,364 --> 00:17:01,945
doesn't go to pure white, and never goes to pure black.

310
00:17:01,945 --> 00:17:03,626
If something goes to pure black, it's

311
00:17:03,626 --> 00:17:05,666
like some weird special material that's

312
00:17:05,666 --> 00:17:07,127
designed to absorb all light.

313
00:17:07,127 --> 00:17:09,228
That rarely ever happens in real life.

314
00:17:09,228 --> 00:17:11,908
So we never allow things to go over these values.

315
00:17:12,798 --> 00:17:15,461
The other thing we found, if you see this red line here,

316
00:17:15,461 --> 00:17:19,806
is that most values fall on the darker end of the spectrum.

317
00:17:19,806 --> 00:17:23,930
And we actually see this error in when people paint as well.

318
00:17:23,930 --> 00:17:28,155
They tend to author their values or their diffuse colors

319
00:17:28,155 --> 00:17:31,918
too light because they're used to seeing them hit by light.

320
00:17:31,918 --> 00:17:34,842
But what happens is you want your diffuse color to be dark.

321
00:17:35,205 --> 00:17:37,947
to allow your light to brighten them up later.

322
00:17:37,947 --> 00:17:42,830
And so this is a common mistake that a lot of artists make

323
00:17:42,830 --> 00:17:45,531
is to author too bright because they're

324
00:17:45,531 --> 00:17:46,512
used to seeing values in the sun.

325
00:17:46,512 --> 00:17:49,353
So this is something that we control very heavily.

326
00:17:49,353 --> 00:17:52,995
This is to show that same image in grayscale

327
00:17:52,995 --> 00:17:55,877
to also show how much color can fool your eyes.

328
00:17:55,877 --> 00:17:57,878
If you look at those red dots, they

329
00:17:57,878 --> 00:17:59,579
look like they should be much brighter

330
00:17:59,579 --> 00:18:01,880
because you read red as bright.

331
00:18:01,880 --> 00:18:03,861
But their value is actually very dark.

332
00:18:04,487 --> 00:18:06,527
And so we do this because we also

333
00:18:06,527 --> 00:18:09,449
know that you can't trust your eyes when it comes to value

334
00:18:09,449 --> 00:18:11,349
or when it comes to sunlight.

335
00:18:11,349 --> 00:18:13,390
So we spend a lot of time with this.

336
00:18:13,390 --> 00:18:16,171
I spend a lot of time talking about it here because honestly,

337
00:18:16,171 --> 00:18:19,313
it is one of the most critical elements of getting

338
00:18:19,313 --> 00:18:22,114
a photorealistic scene.

339
00:18:22,114 --> 00:18:25,455
So we spend a lot of time working on it.

