536
00:28:36,994 --> 00:28:41,817
What we found early on when we had so few polys to deal with is that we would spend all of our

537
00:28:41,817 --> 00:28:47,220
polys on our big objects and ignore our little ones. And what happened was that actually made

538
00:28:47,220 --> 00:28:52,563
everything in our scene feel really cartoony, and you also didn't get a sense of speed.

539
00:28:52,563 --> 00:28:56,525
When you don't see these small grounded objects that the player is familiar with,

540
00:28:56,525 --> 00:29:01,128
then there's no sense of context. There's no feeling for how big a thing is, what its scale is,

541
00:29:01,128 --> 00:29:02,869
or how quickly you're moving against it.

542
00:29:03,307 --> 00:29:09,109
So we actually had to double down on all these small grounding elements, all these small set pieces.

543
00:29:09,109 --> 00:29:22,895
So if we have a building, including the windowsill, if we had a race side object, including these like kind of these booths and these carts, because we want to give you a sense of context and why and how big something is.

544
00:29:22,895 --> 00:29:25,156
And so we actually double down on these.

545
00:29:25,156 --> 00:29:30,898
We actually spend less polys in our large building and our large assets and more polys on these small grounding elements.

546
00:29:31,293 --> 00:29:33,835
to give you that sense of scale and proportion.

547
00:29:33,835 --> 00:29:35,996
This is something that we see often

548
00:29:35,996 --> 00:29:37,978
that beginning students don't do well.

549
00:29:37,978 --> 00:29:39,819
They forget to add these grounding elements.

550
00:29:39,819 --> 00:29:42,301
And as a result, their scenes feel cartoony

551
00:29:42,301 --> 00:29:44,082
because you don't know how large they are.

552
00:29:44,082 --> 00:29:48,265
So finally, I wanna talk about texture.

553
00:29:48,265 --> 00:29:49,787
And again, I saved this one for last

554
00:29:49,787 --> 00:29:52,649
because while this does add a great deal to your scene,

555
00:29:52,649 --> 00:29:54,910
it tends to be the area that students

556
00:29:54,910 --> 00:29:57,372
and even professionals tend to jump to too quickly.

557
00:29:58,113 --> 00:30:02,356
And so texture is obviously important to give you that sense of detail and surface type.

558
00:30:02,356 --> 00:30:04,918
What is this thing going to feel like when I touch it?

559
00:30:04,918 --> 00:30:08,681
But you don't want to go here too early.

560
00:30:08,681 --> 00:30:12,984
So if anyone is familiar with photogrammetry, this has been a groundbreaking technique for us

561
00:30:12,984 --> 00:30:14,725
and something we leverage heavily now.

562
00:30:14,725 --> 00:30:22,551
But this is the, where you take a series of images with your camera and then you use a program

563
00:30:22,551 --> 00:30:24,392
like Agisoft or RealityCapture.

564
00:30:24,790 --> 00:30:27,113
to assemble those pictures into a 3D model.

565
00:30:27,113 --> 00:30:30,638
And so this is an example of a model that we did here.

566
00:30:30,638 --> 00:30:33,322
This is a tree using photogrammetry.

567
00:30:33,322 --> 00:30:36,507
And our artists build almost all their assets

568
00:30:36,507 --> 00:30:38,450
with this technique at this point.

569
00:30:38,450 --> 00:30:40,052
And it's been really awesome for us.

570
00:30:41,088 --> 00:30:45,411
This is another example of where we created this rumble strip using photogrammetry.

571
00:30:45,411 --> 00:30:48,734
And it just gives you and see all these storytelling elements, all this,

572
00:30:48,734 --> 00:30:50,275
all this really nice texture.

573
00:30:50,275 --> 00:30:55,019
This is these are all the little elements that add up to making something look

574
00:30:55,019 --> 00:30:57,481
photorealistic. In this case, we are using a photo,

575
00:30:57,481 --> 00:31:03,586
but as often the details that people miss when they're creating those textures is

576
00:31:03,586 --> 00:31:05,567
all those little details and story elements.

577
00:31:07,996 --> 00:31:10,038
So now I'm going to show you all this in practice.

